1571","about 1550":"about 1550","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wynslade","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Winslade (Hants) or Winslade in East Putford (Devon). The Hants place-name was  <i>Winesflot</i> in 1086,  <i>Winslode</i> in 1399, and had forms in  <i>-a-</i> from the Tudor period. The Devon place-name was recorded as  <i>Wydeslade</i> in 1360 and  <i>Wynslade</i> by 1567."],"variants":[{"name":"Winslet","meanings":["English: apparently a late variant of   Winslade  . Compare James Winslett, 1746, Wm Winslade, 1796 in   IGI   (Farnham, Surrey); Samuel Winslade, 1774, John Winslet, 1785 in   IGI   (Richmond, Surrey)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705202,"age":8,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to churc